{{BLP sources|date=March 2010}} {{Infobox astronaut | image = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people. See [[WP:NONFREE]]. --> | name = Anatoly Pavlovich Artsebarsky | type = Cosmonaut | nationality = Russian | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1956|9|9|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Prosyana]], [[Ukrainian SSR]], [[Soviet Union]] | occupation = [[Test pilot|Test Pilot]] | rank = [[Colonel]], [[Russian Air Force]] | selection = [[List of astronauts by selection#1985|1985]] | time = 144d 15h 21m | mission = [[Soyuz TM-12]], [[List of Mir Expeditions|Mir EO-9]] | insignia = | awards = {{Hero of the Soviet Union}} {{Order of Lenin (medallion)}} |}} '''Anatoly Pavlovich Artsebarsky''' ({{lang-uk|Анатолій Павлович Арцебарський}}) ({{lang-ru|Анатолий Павлович Арцебарский}}; born 9 September 1956) is a former [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[cosmonaut]]<ref>https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/glove-right-hand-soyuz-tm-12-artsebarsky</ref>.
He became a cosmonaut in 1985. Artsebarsky has spent almost 5 months in space on a single spaceflight. In 1991, he flew aboard [[Soyuz TM-12]] and docked with the [[Mir]] Space Station. Artsebarsky and [[Sergei Krikalev]] stayed aboard Mir while the rest of the crew flew back to Earth after eight days. Artsebarsky took six spacewalks during the [[List of Mir Expeditions|Mir EO-9]] mission. He spent over 33 hours walking in space.<ref>[http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/cosmonauts/english/artsebarsky_anatoli.htm Spacefacts]</ref>
During his stay, Artsebarsky constructed a space tower for use with a control module. Artsebarsky and Krikalev were almost stuck at the station. They were in orbit during the [[Soviet coup attempt of 1991]]. For several days, the political situation seriously jeopardised their position.{{Citation needed|date=March 2007}}
He was awarded: * [[Hero of the Soviet Union]] * [[Pilot-Cosmonaut of the USSR]] * [[Order of Lenin]] * [[Medal "For Merit in Space Exploration"]]
==In media== * Artsebarsky is often mentioned in the 2013 movie ''[[Gravity (2013 film)|Gravity]]'', because STS-135 astronaut "Matt" Kowalski tries to break his spacewalking record.
